This paper deals with the problem of generating multiple future frames from a single still image, which is a task related to computer vision (cs.CV). The paper proposes a two-phase design for the prediction task, which involves modeling the multi-flow prediction phase in a variational probabilistic manner and the flow-to-frame synthesis phase as a generative process. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also uses 3D convolutions to learn spatial-temporal relationships, which is a technique commonly used in multimedia (cs.MM) research. Finally, the paper's focus on predicting video sequences suggests that it may also be relevant to robotics (cs.RO) research.
